groundTruth.text: AbstractWe perform a meta analysis of gender differences in the standard windfall gains dictator game (DG) by collecting raw data from 53 studies with 117 conditions, giving us 15,016 unique individual observations. We find that women on average give 4 percentage points more than men (Cohen’s d=0.16), and that this difference decreases to 3.1% points (Cohen’s d=0.13) if we exclude studies where dictators can only give all or nothing. The gender difference is larger if the recipient in the DG is a charity, compared to the standard DG with an anonymous individual as the recipient (a 10.9 versus a 2.3% points gender difference). These effect sizes imply that many individual studies on gender differences are underpowered; the median power in our sample of standard DG studies is only 9% to detect the meta-analytic gender difference at the 5% significance level. Moving forward on this topic, sample sizes should thus be substantially larger than what has been the norm in the past.

templateData.title: Framework for Detecting Subtle Behavioral Differences in Experimental Economics
templateData.description: A structured template for implementing rigorous technical methodologies to detect, quantify, and validate small but meaningful behavioral or psychological differences between demographic groups in controlled economic experiments, with emphasis on statistical power, effect size estimation, and reproducibility

templateProperty.label: Experimental Design Framework
templateProperty.description: The specific experimental design used (e.g., between-subjects, within-subjects, factorial, conjoint, or incentivized field experiment) and its justification for detecting subtle effects

templateProperty.label: Primary Dataset
templateProperty.description: Name of the primary dataset used for analysis, including version or release date if applicable

templateProperty.label: Sample Size Calculation Method
templateProperty.description: Technical method used for power analysis (e.g., G*Power, Monte Carlo simulation, or analytical formula) including the targeted effect size, power (1-β), and alpha level (α)

metadata.originalPropertyName: Target Effect Size (Cohen's d or η²)

templateProperty.label: Target Effect Size (Cohen's d or η²)
templateProperty.description: The minimal detectable effect size (e.g., Cohen's d = 0.2 for 'small' effect) that the study is powered to detect, with justification

templateProperty.label: Achieved Sample Size (per group)
templateProperty.description: Final sample size per demographic group (e.g., gender) after exclusions, with breakdown by key subgroups if applicable

templateProperty.label: Randomization Procedure
templateProperty.description: Detailed technical steps for randomization (e.g., block randomization, stratified randomization, or adaptive randomization) including tools used (e.g., R 'randomizr' package, Python 'scipy.stats')

templateProperty.label: Primary Behavioral Metric
templateProperty.description: The primary quantitative behavioral metric analyzed (e.g., risk aversion score, response time, choice consistency, or cooperation rate) including its operational definition

templateProperty.label: Primary Statistical Test
templateProperty.description: The primary statistical test used (e.g., Welch’s t-test, Mann-Whitney U, linear mixed-effects model) with justification for handling small effects and non-normality

templateProperty.label: Multiple Testing Correction Method
templateProperty.description: Method for controlling family-wise error rate or false discovery rate (e.g., Bonferroni, Holm-Bonferroni, Benjamini-Hochberg) if multiple comparisons are performed

templateProperty.label: Observed Effect Size (with 95% CI)
templateProperty.description: Reported effect size for the primary behavioral difference (e.g., Cohen’s d, Hedges’ g, or η²) with 95% confidence interval

templateProperty.label: Primary p-value (with exact value)
templateProperty.description: Exact p-value for the primary hypothesis test (report as 'p < 0.001' only if p < 0.0001, otherwise provide full decimal)

templateProperty.label: Sensitivity Analysis Method
templateProperty.description: Technical approach for robustness checks (e.g., bootstrapping, Bayesian estimation, or exclusion restrictions) to assess stability of small effects

templateProperty.label: Primary Statistical Software Tool
templateProperty.description: Main software tool used for analysis (e.g., R, Python, Stata, or MATLAB, SPSS, JASP) including version number

templateProperty.label: Replication Code Repository
templateProperty.description: Publicly accessible repository (e.g., GitHub, OSF, or Zenodo) containing analysis code and data preprocessing scripts

templateProperty.label: Pre-Registration DOI
templateProperty.description: DOI or permanent link to the pre-registered analysis plan (e.g., on OSF, AsPredicted, or EGAP)

templateProperty.label: Data Collection Period
templateProperty.description: Start and end dates for primary data collection

templateProperty.label: Demographic Balance Verification
templateProperty.description: Statistical test(s) used to verify balance across groups on covariates (e.g., chi-square for categorical, ANOVA for continuous) with results

templateProperty.label: Bayesian Equivalence Test (if applicable)
templateProperty.description: Bayesian analysis details (e.g., BF₁₀, ROPE, or region of practical equivalence) for assessing evidence for/against small effects

templateProperty.label: Minimal Detectable Effect (MDE) Plot
templateProperty.description: Link to or description of a power analysis plot showing minimal detectable effects at 80% power for the achieved sample size

templateProperty.label: Heterogeneous Treatment Effects Method
templateProperty.description: Technical approach for detecting effect heterogeneity (e.g., Causal Forest, quantile regression, or subgroup analysis) if applicable

templateProperty.label: Data Exclusion Criteria
templateProperty.description: Pre-specified rules for excluding participants/data points (e.g., failed attention checks, outliers > 3SD) with justification

templateProperty.label: Secondary Datasets (if used)
templateProperty.description: Names of additional datasets used for validation or replication, if applicable

templateProperty.label: Replication Attempts
templateProperty.description: Number of independent replication attempts (internal or external) for the primary finding, with summary of consistency
